Multiple Testing: In-class Exercise

bioX R-Summer bootcamp

7/30/2020

Objective

The purpose of this exercise is to make you apply what you learned so far -- both from the hypothesis testing perspective and in terms of linear modeling. This is inspired from a real case study that was presented in the Statistics consulting workshop (STATS 398) over the last few months. The data was confidential, thus the data that we present here is simulated to make it behave a little like the real one. The idea here is to try to see how we could start thinking about leading an analysis of such data.

Setting

Suppose that you are enrolled as a statistics consultant. You get a request for help one afternoon from a doctor in the medical school. The doctor has a dataset of ICU admissions, and wants to investigate whether or not there has been a significant drop in ICU admissions since the beginning of the shelter-in-place in Santa Clara .

His dataset consists of the weekly ICU admissions per disease category since 2019, up to end of April this year: - We have different diseases, and the admission counts per week. - the column "week" indicates which week of the year it is (1-52)

Aggregate Analysis

Solution: Not all diseases show such an effect.

Question 2 Aggregate the data to consider the total number of admissions per week (over all diagnoses). Does there seem to be evidence (from the graph) to support this claim?

Solution: It would seem so.

sum_week= data2 %>% 
  group_by(year, month, week, date, label) %>% 
  summarise(tot_week = sum(value))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year', 'month', 'week', 'date' (override with `.groups` argument)
ggplot(sum_week, aes(x=date, y=tot_week)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour=label)) +
  theme_bw()

Question 3 One of the issues with hospital data is that it could inherently vary due to different factors. Can you think of any factors that might affect the number of admissions? Test if these factors are significant in your current model.

Solution: The questiom is particular that we are interested in is the following: is there a seasonal effect? The weekly plot doesn't seem strikingly different throughout the year. We divide the different months into their corresponding seasons, and fit a Poisson regression model, with a different mean for each season. Denoting as \(X\) the number of ICU admissions per week, this model can be written as: \[ \forall i, X_i \sim Poisson(\lambda + \alpha_2 \mathbf{1}_{G[i]=\text{spring}} + \alpha_3 \mathbf{1}_{G[i]=\text{summer}} + \alpha_4 \mathbf{1}_{G[i]=\text{fall}}) \]

By fitting this model, we realize that the effect of the season is negligible.

sum_week$season = c(rep("Winter",13), rep("Spring",13),
                    rep("Summer",13), rep("Fall",13), rep("Winter",13), rep("Spring",4))
m_season <- glm(tot_week ~ 1. + season , family="poisson",
                data=sum_week %>%filter(label == "Normal"))
summary(m_season)
